---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Base title="The Question Behind the Question" section={8}>
  <SectionHeader n={8} title="The Question Behind the Question" meta="~400w" />

  <div class="prose">

    <p>
      You asked "what's revenue this month?" when you needed to ask something else entirely.
    </p>

    <p>
      This is not a failure of data access or query syntax. It is a failure of question
      formation, and it runs through every era of BI. The spreadsheet analyst pulls
      the wrong cut of data because they answered the presented question, not the
      underlying concern. The dashboard shows revenue and nothing moves. The BI chatbot
      returns the number in two seconds and leaves you no better positioned to decide
      anything.
    </p>

    <p>
      The presenting question is almost never the real question. "What's our churn rate?"
      means "should we invest more in retention?" "What's the support volume this week?"
      means "do I need to hire?" "What did campaign X return?" means "should I run it again,
      or was it a fluke?" The surface question is a placeholder for a decision that
      the person asking has not yet fully articulated, even to themselves.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      <p>The presenting question is almost never the real question. Good BI design
      surfaces the real question. Most tools just answer what you typed.</p>
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      Good analysis practice has always addressed this. A skilled analyst hears "what's
      our churn rate?" and asks: what are you going to do differently depending on the
      answer? If the number is high, what actions are available? If it is low, does that
      change anything? Whose churn — which segments, which cohorts, which acquisition
      channels? The analyst is not being obstructive. They are trying to answer the real
      question, which requires understanding it.
    </p>

    <p>
      Good BI design does the same thing structurally. It does not just surface the metric
      you asked for — it surfaces the metric in the context that makes it useful.
      Revenue this month, compared to budget, compared to last year, flagged if outside
      the normal band. That is not more data. That is the same data with the context
      that turns it from <a href={`${base}section/2`}>a number into a signal</a>.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="Design implication">
      Every metric in your system has a natural set of companion metrics that make it
      interpretable. Churn rate needs cohort breakdown, acquisition channel, and a
      comparison baseline. Designing metrics in isolation produces numbers.
      Designing them in relation produces understanding.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      The hardest version of this problem is when the real question is one the organisation
      is not yet ready to ask. "What's revenue this month?" is sometimes a proxy for
      "are we growing fast enough to raise our next round?" — a question that implies
      specific benchmarks and a specific definition of "enough" that the team has not
      agreed on. Surfacing that would be useful. It would also be uncomfortable.
      So instead the analyst pulls the revenue number and everyone nods.
    </p>

    <p>
      There is no fully automated fix for this. But there are design choices that push
      in the right direction: showing context by default, building in comparison baselines,
      annotating thresholds explicitly, and — perhaps most importantly — building
      instruments that are designed around decisions rather than metrics. The difference
      is subtle but total. A metric is passive. A decision instrument is opinionated.
      It has a point of view about what matters and why, embedded in its design.
    </p>

  </div>
</Base>
